Pointing to the reality of God, and how despite all the evil and selfishness mankind has caused He has met us at every place we have been--no matter how low we have sunk. text: If you approach this from a purely intellectual standpoint you will fall on one side of belief, or the other; yet there will always be a measure of doubt. But those who have taken the step of faith, and experienced the transformational power of Christ in their lives, possess a testimony that cannot be swayed by any number of doubters. Regardless of what happens in and around my life that would otherwise cause me to question God, there is nothing - no comment, evidence, allegation, wisdom - nothing, that can undo the life altering, trajectory changing, profound redirecting that I experienced the moment I asked God into my life. Indeed, the case for Christ is visible in millions of transformed lives, all of whom echo the famous words in John Newton's Amazing Grace: "I once was lost, but now am found; was blind, but now I see."

text: J.D. Rucker  April 16, 2017  â€œThe Case for Christâ€ is a High-Quality Movie in a Genre known for Rotten Reviews: Being a Christian in Hollywood can be difficult. There arenâ€™t a ton  of movies being made today that fit in with a believing actorâ€™s moral  compass. Moreover, thereâ€™s a stigma attached to many actors who  willingly profess their faith just as thereâ€™s a stigma against  conservatives. As such, the average Christian-themed movie is pretty  poorly done from a purely critical perspective. The messages can be  great, but the delivery can be lackluster. Neither Kirk Cameron nor  Nicolas Cage could make one of the most popular Christian book series of  all time successful. The Case for Christ  is different. I was shocked when I saw that it received a 77% critical  response on Rotten Tomatoes until I realized it was only reviewed by 13  critics. Go figure. Nonetheless, it was encouraging so I took my wife to  see it last night. We were familiar with Lee Strobelâ€™s journey from  truth-seeking news reporter to truth-seeing evangelist and author, so we  didnâ€™t go for the sake of the story. As highly selective adults who  have chosen to restrict our movie viewing to ones that fit our worldview  (or that at least donâ€™t attempt to trash it), we wanted to see if it  was the rare â€œwell madeâ€ Christian movie. We were pleased with the results. Both the acting and the cinematography were very good. They delivered  1980 about as well as big-budget films, 70sÂ red Camaro and all.  Nobodyâ€™s going to win an Oscar from this movie, but compared to the  poorly crafted Christian movies of today that have good messages but are  artistically weak, this was a real winner.Â Mike Vogel  delivered the right mix of skepticism and intellect. He was believable  as he struggled in a quest to debunk the resurrection of Jesus Christ. I  wasnâ€™t expecting it based upon some of his previous performances in  cultural garbage flicks likeÂ Cloverfield andÂ The Texas Chainsaw Massacre, but he found his groove with this role. While far from being a critical masterpiece, this will hopefully  bring more attention to the quality of Christian movies. They donâ€™t have  to look like they were made by a high school film studies class, nor  does the dialogue have to sound like carefully crafted proselytizing  disguised as robotic conversations. There needs to be a gelling of  message and art that gets people not only interested in seeing a movie  but that compels them to recommend it.  Hollywood is a cesspool of left-wing manipulation of progressive  propaganda. As a society, weâ€™ve fought through to make  conservative-themed movies likeÂ American SniperÂ andÂ Zero Dark Thirty critical and box office successes. Now we need to do the same for Christian-themed movies. The Case for Christ is a step in the right direction. We need more of them.   JD Rucker  April 16, 2017

text: Stories about Strobel (and Josh McDowell) taking great pains to try and disprove Christianity prior to converting are bunk. Check out these admissions from McDowell in the earliest versions of his personal testimony: https://infidels.org/library/modern/ed_babinski/experience.html#mcdowell  As for Lee Strobel he admits in his book, THE CASE FOR CHRIST, that he wrote it to "retrace and expand upon his journey." So we don't know what his original journey to allegedly disprove Christianity consisted of, or how little he knew about the NT, history or philosophy prior to converting. THE CASE FOR CHRIST was composed 16 years or more after he'd already converted and been working as a minister at his church for years. It looks like his original journey consisted of simply reading a few apologist's books by conservative Christians, books probably suggested by his wife who was probably asking friends at church for "good books for my husband to read." Freedom From Atheism Foundation (FFAF)    ASK STROBEL WHAT HE KNEW ABOUT RELIGION AND BIBLICAL STUDIES AND EXACTLY WHAT HE READ _PRIOR_ TO CONVERTING

text: One would think that some sort of "case" would have been reflected in this trailer.  But nothing even remotely compelling (of course).  Even if "Jesus" existed and literally died on the cross, what exactly does that prove with regard to the existence of "God" or that he had to "die for our sins," which is a complete absurdity.  No one can reasonably explain that one, for sure.  Why this man would have to suffer so horrifically ... for us?  And "the son of God," how he must have loved his son to allow such a thing.  It simply isn't true, and likely very little of the old book literally happened.  Symbolic, sure, many lessons (like so many other books, new and old).  But the old book isn't speaking of a literal sky monster (try to argue against that rationally), it's speaking of all of us, collectively and individually.  "MIracles" and other phenomena, oh yes, that's good stuff.  I've experienced many things in that regard myself.  Studies have even shown that prayer works.  What studies can't show is that all of this is due to some fairy tale sky god.  But what we have proven is that "believe and it shall be so" declaration.  The body/mind connection, the placebo effect...  WE CREATE THE MIRACLES, both collectively and individually.  The old book is about us.  Period.

text: God created us, if you want proof of God, look in the mirror.  For those who ask, so God sat down mapped out our DNA, our universe, etc., etc., etc.  Maybe he did, just because it would be too large of a task for you, doesn't mean it was for God.  Obviously God is far more genius or powerful than any man, hence, why he was able to create the universe and map out the creation of life.  I really love the logic, it can't be proven, therefore it's false.  Not too far in the past, there were people who said the same about the earth being round.  It could not be proven, therefore, the earth was flat and anyone who believed otherwise was a fool and would fall off the edge of the earth if they walked far enough.  If you open your eyes and mind enough, you will see proof of God everywhere, including your mirror.  God is real, 100%.  Angels are real 100% and for those who have faith, those who trust God, our father, God and the Angels who he sends to be our guardians, are more than happy to make themselves known.  With love and faith and trust, pray and ye shall receive.  I have many times, and that's not science, it's not coincidence, it's God.  In fact, I have a friend who was an atheist.  Her life never seemed to go right.  Then one day, a year after her divorce from an abusive man who manipulated her into living a life of sin, claiming if she loved him, she would give him threesomes and attend private orgies; she met a man at her sister's birthday party.  He was a Marine on leave.  He was also a Christian.  They dated, and she began to attend, skeptically, his church.  She allowed herself to be welcomed into his church.  A year later they were married, and she became a devout Christian, and since she became a believer, she laughs at atheists, saying that every single thing she prayed for God answered.  A beautiful new home, and recently, a healthy beautiful baby girl.  She wrote me one day telling me that since she opened her heart and life to God, nothing but miracles have happened in her life, including the struggling baking business she tried to start with her first marriage, took off and she was even asked to be on their local morning news station to show how to make the perfect cupcake.  After she welcomed God into her life, her life has been one blessing after another, and now five years later, she still looks like the happiest woman in the world.  For those who think tragedy, war, etc., would not happen if there was a God, I've got a newsflash, God does not make any of that happen, he gave us free will, and we, stupid humans, make all the tragedy happen.  God put us here and gave us free will, he does not interfere with the stupid mistakes and ideas we create.  As for illnesses, like a child getting cancer, yes, it's sad, but maybe that's the life that child was meant to live in order to help find new cures, new treatments, etc.  We have the Amber Alert because little Amber was abducted and murdered.  Maybe that was her destiny, so other children could be saved.  An innocent child is murdered by a stray drive-by gang shooting.  It's heartbreaking, but maybe the child's destiny was to make sure a brother, or nephew, someone in that family does not go down the same path, but instead becomes someone who will fight to end the violence and save the lives of other innocent children.  Just because we don't understand God's plan, doesn't mean that God is either cruel or doesn't exist.  Finally, my dear atheists, your belief system is a religion, so please stop preaching that religion is stupid, because atheism is a religion, a religion of disbelief, but a religion nevertheless.

text: If you never search for God then you will never find out if God is real or not. Do you really want to come to the end of your life without knowing?  I searched because I was hungry to know. I investigated all the major religions except Christianity but did not find God in any of them. I avoided Christianity because I was biased against it.  In a last desperate effort - I decided to be fair "and give God a chance - if God was real " and Christianity was the way.  I laid a Bible on the table in front of me and said God , if you are real - show me. To the best of my ability I laid aside my bias and tried to read with an open mind. I began at page 1 and decided to give God a chance and to read to the last page. If I got there and had not found God then I was ready to give up on the search.  I got about 1/2 thru with no change. Then in the Psalms things changed. I read in Psalm 22 " they pierced my hands and my feet." I knew this had to be about Christ - even though it was written 1,000 years before Christ was born.  Only God could do that - and it became clear to me that Christ suffered that for me because He loved me. I said - if you love me that much I will follow you.

text: Just finished watching the film. If I had to describe it to a friend, I would say it is the story of one man with remarkably low standards for evidence on an unremarkable journey to shield himself from the obvious and glaring logical fallacies he manages to accept. In the end, he is able to overcome the demand for reason and evidence that even a child would demand before accepting the most extraordinary claims it is possible to imagine.Â   If I applied the same threshold for accepting a supernatural claim as Lee used for Christian mythology, it is hard to imagine a supernatural claim I WOULDN'T accept as true.  I must confess, I enjoy watching these fanciful religious films which seek to portray skeptics and non-believers in ways they desperately would like them to be: arrogant and angry people who put on a masquerade of critical thinking, inevitably more satisfied by the theistic claims the more they are unpacked, instead of what is typically the case; they've never heard the ghost of a compelling argument or seen any reason to accept what would seem to be objectively inconsistent and absurd claims.  I'd just as soon watch a Flat Earth film about a "skeptic" who comes to accept the truth of the disk shaped planet he so desperately needed to come to know.

text: I am an European atheist and I have watched the movie. It was slightly better than I expected, although it was still very bad. The reality is much different, especially in Europe. There are dozens of religious beliefs here. Some people are very liberal christian, others are agnostics, a lot of people simply don't give a shit. You will find very little people who will say they are atheists. That is why this debate is so irrelevant for them, they realize that reality is not as black and white as evangelical christians want it to be. The idea that you will be send to heaven because of some thoughts you have in your brain is so ridiculous they wouldn't even think about it.   About the debate in the movie: That had absolutely nothing to do with objectivity. Only christian apologists are talking and Strobel asks questions no atheists would ever ask. Some of the arguments have been debunked a thousand times, but they are still used by apologists. The idea that the apostels wouldn't die for a lie looks like an interesting argument, except that we have no sources at all that John, Peter (or even Paul) did indeed die for their christian beliefs. text: I wrote this underneath someone else's comment, but it's worth putting where others can see it. Please discuss civilly. I would really love to hear peoples' thoughts.  The idea of "something coming from nothing" is actually the only logical explanation for God as Creator. Let me explain:  Think of the entire world as a painting, like the Mona Lisa. The Painter, Leonardo DaVinci, is the creator. The world didn't come from nothing, just as the paint in the painting didn't come from nothing. But it came from a different KIND of substance, one that, if Mona as the paint in the painting was able to think for herself, she would be unable comprehend this kind of substance because the paint of her own world is all she knows.  In order for the painter to be the creator of the painting, he has to exist outside the painting. Time, space, and matter are the governing foundation of our existence, but they do not apply to God because he created them. To say that God has to be bound to creation in order to be a creator, is to say that Leonardo DaVinci would need to be made of canvas-bound paint in order to be a painter.

text: As a Christian, I'm consistently frustrated and disappointed by the production values of films with pro-Christian themes. The first thing a person notices, when they watch trailers for them, is the utter non-recognizability  of both the actors and the directors of these genre of films. Every Christian film ends up with actors/actresses/directors that have either no other current body of work, or perhaps they had film parts over 20 years ago. So, why is this?  Well, it's because, in a nutshell, that Hollywood despises Christianity. The vast majority of the people in the film industry simply hate Christians, and so they refuse to  produce films that even acknowledge them.    And, because they despise Christians, they assume the rest of the country does as well, and they assume there is zero marketability for Christian-based films. Thus, we end up with  small-time directors, producers, and third-rate actors, using indie film companies, making any and all Christian films.   And, this is absurd.  In the USA, there are 240 MILLION Christians.   This is a MASSIVE potential commercial market, yet Hollywood virtually ignores it.

text: Looking back on it, this was a really good Christian movie, on par with the production value of secular Hollywood films. It wasn't over dramatic and the acting wasn't bad like most other Christian films. Most of all, it isn't one of those that portrays the opposing side as total a-holes, it carefully considers the point of view of everyone who was involved in this story and focuses on evidence found by the real journalist, Lee Strobel. Unlike other Christian films, this is a great watch for religious and non-religious people alike.
